# Backend Design Patterns (Guidelines)

Patterns are optional tools used only when they reduce complexity or duplication.

---

## 1. Dependency Injection
Use DI by default to decouple components and improve testability.

Avoid overuse in trivial objects where it adds no value.

---

## 2. Repository Pattern
Use when data access logic must be separated from domain logic.

Avoid when simple CRUD does not benefit from abstraction.

---

## 3. Factory Pattern
Use when object creation contains non-trivial or conditional logic.

Avoid when constructors are sufficient.

---

## 4. Strategy Pattern
Use when multiple interchangeable behaviors are required.

Avoid when behavior is stable and does not vary.

---

## 5. Encapsulation Rule
Expose only public interfaces between modules.
Do not leak internal implementation details across layers.

---

## 6. Design Principle
Prefer direct and simple implementations.
Introduce patterns only when they clearly reduce complexity or duplication.